<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Morphological characters are concordant with the description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cairns" authorityYear="2018" class="Anthozoa" family="Primnoidae" genus="Calyptrophora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Calyptrophora distolos" order="Pennatulacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="distolos">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Calyptrophora distolos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" author="Cairns, SD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 43" refId="B13" refString="Cairns, SD, 2018. Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific. Zootaxa 4532 (1): 1 - 43, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" title="Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" volume="4532" year="2018">Cairns 2018</bibRefCitation>
). In addition to the paired polyps mentioned in the species description, this specimen also presents a few whorls with three or four polyps (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Calyptrophora distolos Cairns, 2018. Specimen CCZ _ 132: A in situ image B whole colony C detail of polyps before preservation. Scale bars: 2 cm (A, B); 5 mm (C). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A); Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B, C)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716344" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">18C</figureCitation>
). Polyps are downward-oriented, therefore belonging to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">wyvillei</emphasis>
complex (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" author="Cairns, SD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 43" refId="B13" refString="Cairns, SD, 2018. Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific. Zootaxa 4532 (1): 1 - 43, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" title="Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" volume="4532" year="2018">Cairns 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. persephone" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="persephone">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. persephone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Cairns, 2015, which has been described for the UK-1 and BGR areas in the CCZ (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0340-x" author="Cairns, SD" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="141 - 150" refId="B12" refString="Cairns, SD, 2015. New abyssal Primnoidae (Anthozoa: Octocorallia) from the Clarion-Clipperton Fracture Zone, equatorial northeastern Pacific. Marine Biodiversity 46 (1): 141 - 150, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0340-x" title="New abyssal Primnoidae (Anthozoa: Octocorallia) from the Clarion-Clipperton Fracture Zone, equatorial northeastern Pacific." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0340-x" volume="46" year="2015">Cairns 2015</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. persephone" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="persephone">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. persephone</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised as having polyps oriented upwards, therefore belonging to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">japonica</emphasis>
complex, and that are consistently arranged in whorls of three or four, with each basal scale bearing two prominent distal spines. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cairns" authorityYear="2018" class="Anthozoa" family="Primnoidae" genus="Calyptrophora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Calyptrophora distolos" order="Pennatulacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="distolos">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Calyptrophora distolos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from the Enigma Seamount, south of Guam, at 3737 m depth, and has also been recorded for American Samoa at 2994 m depth (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" author="Cairns, SD" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 43" refId="B13" refString="Cairns, SD, 2018. Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific. Zootaxa 4532 (1): 1 - 43, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" title="Primnoidae (Cnidaria: Octocorallia: Calcaxonia) of the Okeanos Explorer expeditions (CAPSTONE) to the central Pacific." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4532.1.1" volume="4532" year="2018">Cairns 2018</bibRefCitation>
). There are no genetic sequences available for other specimens of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. distolos" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="distolos">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. distolos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the sequences generated here cluster with other species of the genus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Rooted Bayesian phylogeny of Octocorallia. Concatenated (16 S, COI, mtMutS, NADH 2) median consensus BEAST tree with posterior probability (PP) and bootstrap (BS) values indicated. Only values of PP&gt; 0.70 and BS&gt; 50 are shown, with values of PP&gt; 0.95 and BS&gt; 90 indicated with a circle. Nodes not recovered on the RAxML tree are indicated with a hyphen. Sequences generated in this study are highlighted in violet." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716341" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">15</figureCitation>
). However, the genus was not recovered as monophyletic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The specimen was found attached to a polymetallic crust on the slope of a seamount on APEI 4, at 4124 m depth.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A similar primnoid morphotype (i.e., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cairns" authorityYear="2018" class="Anthozoa" family="Primnoidae" genus="Calyptrophora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Calyptrophora distolos" order="Pennatulacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="distolos">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Calyptrophora distolos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. inc., ALC_016) was catalogued from seabed imagery (also collected on a seamount) in the eastern CCZ (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5194/bg-17-2657-2020" author="Cuvelier, D" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B19" refString="Cuvelier, D, Ribeiro, PA, Ramalho, SP, Kersken, D, Martinez Arbizu, P, Colaco, A, 2020. Are seamounts refuge areas for fauna from polymetallic nodule fields? Biogeosciences 17(9): 2657-2680. https://doi.org/10.5194/bg-17-2657-2020" title="Are seamounts refuge areas for fauna from polymetallic nodule fields? Biogeosciences 17 (9): 2657 - 2680." url="https://doi.org/10.5194/bg-17-2657-2020" year="2020">Cuvelier et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), but not in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Order 
